According to the data description, the null values for the qualitative data correspond to not having that feature in the house, so filling that with a new categorical value, DNE, should be a good treatment.

The missing quantitative data is bit more interesting. We can fill those null values with 0 and I think it should have little impact on a decision tree. If we were to use linear regression it could be problematic, especially with GarageYrBlt, and maybe LotFrontage. With the amount of 0 values from MasVnrArea, it's questionable how much this feature contributes and if the data is even valid, since all but 4 houses have a Masonry veneer type but more than half have no recorded area. This feature may be a good candidate for removal.

Quantitative Data¶

In [184]:
plt.figure(figsize=(25, 25))

    sns.regplot(x=data[quantitative[n]], y=data.SalePrice, line_kws={'color':'cyan'}, scatter_kws={'color':'red', 'alpha': 0.3})

MSSubClass is the type of dwelling, and it is identified by numbers. This feature could be re ordered, made into a categorical feature, or removed(as the type of dwelling is also reflected in the other features).

KitchenAbvGr also has a strange behavior since the majority have 1, so it's highly influenced by the tail of the distribution. OverallCond suffers from a similar problem, and the regression line is the opposite of what we expect.

GarageYrBlt seems to suffer from the 0s we filled in for null values. This feature could potentially be represented in GarageCars or GarageArea, and removed entirely or fill in the null values with something else. Two possibilities are the mean of the other values, or the YearBuilt

In [185]:
for n in range(0, len(data.GarageYrBlt)):
    if data.GarageYrBlt[n] == 0:
        data.loc[n, 'GarageYrBlt'] = data.YearBuilt[n]
